1
00:02:14,524 --> 00:02:16,456
The communion of saints

2
00:02:16,524 --> 00:02:19,854
forgiveness of sins,
the resurrection of the body

3
00:02:19,924 --> 00:02:21,856
and life everlasting.

4
00:02:21,924 --> 00:02:24,220
Amen.

5
00:02:24,291 --> 00:02:26,280
Let us pray.

6
00:02:28,258 --> 00:02:30,689
Lord, have mercy upon us.

7
00:02:30,757 --> 00:02:32,689
Christ, have mercy upon us.

8
00:02:32,757 --> 00:02:33,902
Lord, have mercy upon us.

9
00:02:33,942 --> 00:02:35,087
Amen.

10
00:02:35,158 --> 00:02:37,350
Our Father.

11
00:02:37,423 --> 00:02:39,651
Our Father, which art in heaven,
hallowed...

12
00:02:39,724 --> 00:02:42,656
<i>Dear God, there's something</i>
<i>I want to ask you.</i>

13
00:02:42,724 --> 00:02:44,656
<i>Of course you know what it is</i>

14
00:02:44,724 --> 00:02:47,656
<i>because you know everything that's</i>
<i>going to happen before it happens.</i>

15
00:02:47,724 --> 00:02:50,156
<i>So there's really no need to ask you.</i>

16
00:02:50,224 --> 00:02:52,655
<i>But I thought I'd ask you in any case.</i>

17
00:02:52,724 --> 00:02:55,156
<i>Now, you know that I believe in you.</i>

18
00:02:55,224 --> 00:02:58,451
<i>But I was wondering</i>
<i>if you could give me just a little sign.</i>

19
00:03:04,258 --> 00:03:07,190
<i>I mean, I'm not saying that</i>
<i>if you don't give me the sign</i>

20
00:03:07,258 --> 00:03:10,587
<i>that I won't believe in you.</i>
<i>I'm not threatening you or anything like that.</i>

21
00:03:10,657 --> 00:03:13,589
<i>But please, please,</i>
<i>give me enough courage</i>

22
00:03:13,657 --> 00:03:16,714
<i>to speak to Margaret Spencer</i>
<i>and get to know her.</i>

23
00:03:16,790 --> 00:03:19,881
O God,
make clean our hearts within us.

24
00:03:19,957 --> 00:03:22,718
And take not thy holy spirit from us.

25
00:03:26,957 --> 00:03:28,718
<i>Miss Spencer,</i>

26
00:03:29,990 --> 00:03:32,979
<i>I wonder if I could have</i>
<i>a word with you.</i>

27
00:03:33,057 --> 00:03:34,955
<i>There's something</i>
<i>I've got to tell you,</i>

28
00:03:35,024 --> 00:03:38,286
<i>something I've got to</i>
<i>bring out into the open.</i>

29
00:03:38,358 --> 00:03:40,789
<i>I've been bottling it up</i>
<i>inside me too long</i>

30
00:03:40,857 --> 00:03:44,483
<i>and there's no point</i>
<i>in hiding it anymore.</i>

31
00:03:44,557 --> 00:03:47,990
<i>For six years now,</i>
<i>ever since you came to Wimpy's,</i>

32
00:03:48,057 --> 00:03:50,921
<i>I've been in love with you.</i>

33
00:03:50,990 --> 00:03:53,785
<i>I only live to hear your voice.</i>

34
00:03:53,857 --> 00:03:57,221
One cheeseburger, one shanty,
one portion french fries.

35
00:03:57,291 --> 00:03:59,060
<i>Each time you speak</i>

36
00:03:59,100 --> 00:04:03,417
<i>it's like a thousand violins</i>
<i>playing in the halls of heaven.</i>

37
00:04:03,491 --> 00:04:05,457
<i>I love you, Miss Spencer.</i>

38
00:04:05,523 --> 00:04:08,751
<i>I love everything about you:</i>

39
00:04:08,824 --> 00:04:13,586
<i>the way you walk, your sweet smile,</i>
<i>your easy grace and charm.</i>

40
00:04:13,657 --> 00:04:17,488
Wimpy Burgers twice, one M.R.,
one well, heavy on the onions.

41
00:04:17,557 --> 00:04:21,081
<i>I wish I could take you away</i>
<i>from all this.</i>

42
00:04:21,157 --> 00:04:23,560
<i>I'd like us to start</i>
<i>a new life together.</i>

43
00:04:23,600 --> 00:04:28,086
<i>A little house of our own, a car,</i>
<i>the two of us against the world,</i>

44
00:04:28,157 --> 00:04:30,952
<i>joined forevermore</i>
<i>in holy wedlock.</i>

45
00:04:36,500 --> 00:04:40,000
-Miss Spencer!
-What?

46
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:47,250
Nothing.

47
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:26,260
Good evening.

48
00:05:26,300 --> 00:05:29,200
I couldn't help noticing that you were
making an unsuccessful suicide bid.

49
00:05:29,400 --> 00:05:31,260
What are you doing in my room?
What do you want?

50
00:05:31,300 --> 00:05:32,486
I'm here to help you, Mr. Moon.

51
00:05:32,557 --> 00:05:35,560
-I don't want any help. Please go away.
-Oh, all right.

52
00:05:35,600 --> 00:05:39,086
I just thought you might be interested
in a little matter of a million pounds.

53
00:05:39,157 --> 00:05:40,747
A million pounds?

54
00:05:44,224 --> 00:05:46,655
Don't let me interfere with
your doing away with yourself.

55
00:05:46,724 --> 00:05:48,260
What's this about a million pounds?

56
00:05:48,300 --> 00:05:50,060
-May I come in?
-Yes, please do.

57
00:05:50,100 --> 00:05:53,815
Thank you. I wonder
if you'd mind taking my cloak.

58
00:05:54,700 --> 00:05:57,200
Hang it somewhere dry,
would you?

59
00:05:58,523 --> 00:06:01,115
-Might I sit down?
-Oh, do.

60
00:06:01,191 --> 00:06:02,060
Thank you.

61
00:06:03,100 --> 00:06:05,700
It's a very nasty little place
you've got here.

62
00:06:05,800 --> 00:06:08,260
Oh. Thank you.
What's this about a million pounds?

63
00:06:08,300 --> 00:06:09,560
Oh, a million pounds, yes.

64
00:06:09,600 --> 00:06:12,614
You remember
your great-great-great-grandfather?

65
00:06:12,690 --> 00:06:16,464
-Well, I never even met my father.
-How very sad.

66
00:06:16,504 --> 00:06:17,979
Excuse me.

67
00:06:20,257 --> 00:06:23,689
In all events, your great-great-great-
grandfather, Ephraim Moon,

68
00:06:23,757 --> 00:06:26,689
sailed for Australia in 1782
on a ship of the line.

69
00:06:26,757 --> 00:06:29,053
Set himself up as an apothecary.

70
00:06:29,124 --> 00:06:31,160
The business flourished
and by the time he died

71
00:06:31,200 --> 00:06:34,056
it was worth something
in the region of Â£2,000.

72
00:06:34,124 --> 00:06:36,386
-A large amount in those days.
-Yes.

73
00:06:36,458 --> 00:06:38,760
Your great-great-grandfather,
Cedric Moon,

74
00:06:38,800 --> 00:06:41,260
by skillful management
and careful husbandry

75
00:06:41,300 --> 00:06:43,390
increased that sum
a hundredfold.

76
00:06:43,458 --> 00:06:47,049
This, in turn, was inherited
by your great-grandfather, Desmond Moon,

77
00:06:47,124 --> 00:06:49,386
who expanded,
diversified

78
00:06:49,458 --> 00:06:54,549
and built up a personal fortune
of well over a million pounds.

79
00:06:54,623 --> 00:06:56,453
Oh. That's a lot of money.

80
00:06:56,523 --> 00:06:59,251
A great deal of money, Mr. Moon.

81
00:06:59,324 --> 00:07:01,881
And this gigantic sum

82
00:07:01,957 --> 00:07:05,219
was inherited by your grandfather,
Hubert Moon,

83
00:07:05,291 --> 00:07:09,053
who returned to London and frittered it away
on wine, women and loose living.

84
00:07:11,191 --> 00:07:13,560
Where does that leave me,
then?

85
00:07:13,600 --> 00:07:16,000
Penniless and
on the brink of suicide.

86
00:07:20,800 --> 00:07:22,860
You get out of here
before I call the police.

87
00:07:22,900 --> 00:07:25,700
-Before you call the what?
-The police.

88
00:07:25,800 --> 00:07:28,622
You realise that suicide
is a criminal offence.

89
00:07:28,690 --> 00:07:31,500
In less enlightened times
they'd have hung you for it.

90
00:07:33,600 --> 00:07:35,360
Look, exactly what do you want?

91
00:07:35,400 --> 00:07:38,460
I told you. Seriously,
I want to help you.

92
00:07:38,500 --> 00:07:41,660
Unburden yourself. It does you good
to share your problems.

93
00:07:41,700 --> 00:07:44,660
What interest is it to you?

94
00:07:44,700 --> 00:07:45,960
Please, go away!

95
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:48,017
I'm interested in everybody.

96
00:07:48,091 --> 00:07:51,216
Please tell me. What drove you
to this desperate act?

97
00:07:51,291 --> 00:07:53,722
All right, I'll tell you.
I'm miserable.

98
00:07:53,790 --> 00:07:56,722
I've got a boring job,
no money, no prospects.

99
00:07:56,790 --> 00:08:00,060
I haven't got a girlfriend,
I can't get to know anyone,

100
00:08:00,100 --> 00:08:03,223
no one wants to get to know me
and everything is hopeless.

101
00:08:03,291 --> 00:08:05,223
All right? Satisfied?

102
00:08:05,291 --> 00:08:08,314
And if you really want to help me,
you can get me a sock for this pipe.

103
00:08:08,391 --> 00:08:11,800
-Oh, yes. They're in the top
left-hand drawer, aren't they?  -Yeah.

104
00:08:12,300 --> 00:08:16,060
But suicide, Mr. Moon?
Really, really, really.

105
00:08:16,100 --> 00:08:18,156
That's the last thing
you should do.

106
00:08:18,224 --> 00:08:21,156
Don't you think
it's taking the easy way out?

107
00:08:21,224 --> 00:08:23,156
Easy way out?

108
00:08:23,224 --> 00:08:25,156
What's easy about it?

109
00:08:25,224 --> 00:08:27,655
Look, the bleedin' pipe's broken.

110
00:08:27,724 --> 00:08:29,656
Can't even manage to kill myself.

111
00:08:29,724 --> 00:08:32,656
Let's face it, Mr. Moon,
you're a complete failure.

112
00:08:32,724 --> 00:08:34,400
Yes.

113
00:08:35,000 --> 00:08:37,056
I'll fix that.

114
00:08:37,124 --> 00:08:39,715
You know that million pounds
I mentioned?

115
00:08:39,790 --> 00:08:41,722
I wasn't joking.

116
00:08:41,790 --> 00:08:43,949
I could give you that
and more.

117
00:08:44,024 --> 00:08:46,360
Everything you've ever seen
in the advertisements:

118
00:08:46,400 --> 00:08:48,260
fast, white convertibles,

119
00:08:48,300 --> 00:08:51,456
blonde women,
their hair trailing in the wind,

120
00:08:51,523 --> 00:08:53,456
wafer-thin after-dinner chocolates.

121
00:08:53,523 --> 00:08:56,060
If you had all that,
would you be any happier?

122
00:08:56,100 --> 00:08:57,960
What are you on about?

123
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:01,188
Would the words "Prince of Darkness"
mean anything to you?

124
00:09:01,257 --> 00:09:04,155
Beelzebub? Mephistopheles?
The horned one?

125
00:09:06,300 --> 00:09:08,290
I know.
You've escaped from somewhere.

126
00:09:08,358 --> 00:09:10,060
No, I haven't, Mr. Moon.

127
00:09:10,100 --> 00:09:14,085
I'm the horned one, the devil.
Let me give you my card.

128
00:09:17,358 --> 00:09:21,400
Oh, yes, the devil. Of course.
Silly old me.

129
00:09:21,600 --> 00:09:24,519
Cor blimey!
I left my hankie at Wimpy's.

130
00:09:24,590 --> 00:09:27,750
-I wonder if you'll excuse me.
-Don't rush away, Mr. Moon.

131
00:09:27,824 --> 00:09:30,120
You're a nutcase.
You're a bleedin' nutcase.

132
00:09:30,191 --> 00:09:32,660
They said the same of Jesus Christ,
Freud and Galileo.

133
00:09:32,700 --> 00:09:34,956
They said it
of a lot of nutcases too.

134
00:09:35,024 --> 00:09:37,956
You're not as stupid as you look,
are you, Mr. Moon?

135
00:09:38,024 --> 00:09:41,184
What can I do to convince you
that I'm the devil?

136
00:09:41,257 --> 00:09:44,189
Supposing I granted you
your dearest wish here and now.

137
00:09:44,257 --> 00:09:46,382
What about that girl at Wimpy's?

138
00:09:46,458 --> 00:09:47,750
Margaret Spencer?

139
00:09:47,790 --> 00:09:49,083
Yes.

140
00:09:49,157 --> 00:09:51,089
How do you know about her?

141
00:09:51,157 --> 00:09:53,060
And how do you know
so much about me,

142
00:09:53,100 --> 00:09:55,589
where my socks are
and who my grandfather was?

143
00:09:55,657 --> 00:09:58,283
I told you.
I've been taking an interest in you.

144
00:09:58,358 --> 00:10:01,085
Look, well, supposing I

145
00:10:01,157 --> 00:10:02,760
gave you a trial wish.

146
00:10:02,800 --> 00:10:05,460
No obligation on your part.
Just to get acquainted.

147
00:10:05,500 --> 00:10:08,419
Is there anything in the world
you really desire?

148
00:10:08,491 --> 00:10:10,457
-Margaret Spencer.
-Aside from Margaret Spencer.

149
00:10:10,523 --> 00:10:13,115
We'll save her till later,
when you sign. Anything else?

150
00:10:13,500 --> 00:10:17,623
A Frobisher and Gleason
raspberry-flavoured ice lolly.

151
00:10:17,690 --> 00:10:19,260
Very well, Mr. Moon.

152
00:10:19,300 --> 00:10:22,986
Conclusively to prove that
I am indeed the unholy one

153
00:10:23,057 --> 00:10:25,716
a Frobisher and Gleason
raspberry-flavoured ice lolly

154
00:10:25,790 --> 00:10:27,722
shall be yours

155
00:10:27,790 --> 00:10:28,960
in a trice.

156
00:10:29,000 --> 00:10:39,400
-[Snaps fingers]
-Here you are.
-Thank you.

157
00:10:39,800 --> 00:10:44,000
Have you got sixpence?
I've only got a million-pound note.

158
00:10:44,324 --> 00:10:46,256
-Thank you.
-Ta.

159
00:10:46,324 --> 00:10:48,812
-Convinced?
-Do me a favour.

160
00:10:48,890 --> 00:10:50,660
I could have done that myself.

161
00:10:50,700 --> 00:10:52,879
I thought you were gonna
conjure it up.

162
00:10:52,957 --> 00:10:56,548
You're just like all the rest, aren't you?
No proof is good enough.

163
00:10:56,623 --> 00:10:58,646
I want a miracle.

164
00:10:58,724 --> 00:11:00,656
A rain of toads or something.

165
00:11:00,724 --> 00:11:04,157
All right then.
Which of the cheap tricks is it gonna be?

166
00:11:04,224 --> 00:11:06,655
Wine into water?
Stick into serpent?

167
00:11:06,724 --> 00:11:09,554
How about flying through space
at the speed of light?

168
00:11:09,623 --> 00:11:13,147
How about you checking in to the nearest
loony bin for a few weeks' holiday?

169
00:11:13,224 --> 00:11:15,655
O ye of little faith, Moon.

170
00:11:15,724 --> 00:11:18,054
You're not wearing
nylon underwear, are you?

171
00:11:18,124 --> 00:11:20,460
-Why?
-It disintegrates at high speeds.

172
00:11:20,500 --> 00:11:22,160
Prepare yourself.

173
00:11:22,200 --> 00:11:24,486
The magic words: L B J.

174
00:11:26,623 --> 00:11:28,885
Here, my ice lolly's melted.

175
00:11:30,291 --> 00:11:32,060
You really must be the devil.

176
00:11:32,100 --> 00:11:35,000
-Incarnate. How do you do?
-Oh. How do you do?

177
00:11:41,600 --> 00:11:43,713
Where are we? Is this hell?

178
00:11:43,790 --> 00:11:45,585
Just my London headquarters.

179
00:11:46,300 --> 00:11:48,560
That's not your name, is it?

180
00:11:48,600 --> 00:11:51,000
George Spiggott?

181
00:11:51,600 --> 00:11:55,260
Come on in. It's one of my many earthly
pseudoplumes, or nom de nyms.

182
00:11:55,300 --> 00:11:56,960
I thought you were called Lucifer.

183
00:11:57,000 --> 00:11:59,456
I know. The Bringer of the Light,
it used to be.

184
00:11:59,523 --> 00:12:01,060
Sounded a bit puffy to me.

185
00:12:01,100 --> 00:12:02,960
God keeps changing his name too,
you know.

186
00:12:03,000 --> 00:12:04,460
He used to be called "the Word".

187
00:12:04,500 --> 00:12:07,560
-Yeah. "In the beginning was the Word".
-"And the Word was God".

188
00:12:07,600 --> 00:12:10,060
Was there just a word
hanging about in space then?

189
00:12:10,100 --> 00:12:12,960
I suppose so.
I wasn't there.

190
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:15,951
-What's it mean,"the Word"?
-What does "Stanley Moon" mean?

191
00:12:16,024 --> 00:12:18,013
Evening, Anger.

192
00:12:22,500 --> 00:12:25,300
It's all right, Anger.
He's with me.

193
00:12:25,623 --> 00:12:27,300
Come in, Mr. Moon.

194
00:12:27,623 --> 00:12:30,555
I'd like you to meet Anger.
He works for me.

195
00:12:30,623 --> 00:12:32,660
How do you do?
Pleased to meet you.

196
00:12:32,700 --> 00:12:34,500
Watch it, that's all.

197
00:12:38,057 --> 00:12:39,860
This is the Club Room.

198
00:12:39,900 --> 00:12:43,887
It's quite nicely decorated
and painted. Early Hitler.

199
00:12:43,957 --> 00:12:45,889
Now, what about
my little proposition?

200
00:12:45,957 --> 00:12:49,287
All I want from you is something
you probably don't even realise you have.

201
00:12:49,358 --> 00:12:51,290
I'm talking about your soul.

202
00:12:51,358 --> 00:12:53,290
-My soul?
-Yes.

203
00:12:53,358 --> 00:12:55,290
Like you collect moths,

204
00:12:55,358 --> 00:12:57,290
I collect souls.

205
00:12:57,358 --> 00:13:00,000
I'd like to add yours
to my collection.

206
00:13:00,200 --> 00:13:03,222
-What are you doing?
-Just a bit of routine mischief.

207
00:13:03,291 --> 00:13:05,257
Now then,
what about your soul?

208
00:13:05,324 --> 00:13:09,653
Well, I don't know where it is
or how to get hold of it.

209
00:13:09,724 --> 00:13:11,000
Exactly.

210
00:13:11,100 --> 00:13:15,781
And all I want from you is the exclusive
global and universal rights to it.

211
00:13:16,924 --> 00:13:19,083
But if you took it out,
wouldn't it hurt?

212
00:13:19,157 --> 00:13:21,089
It's a painless operation.

213
00:13:21,157 --> 00:13:23,554
And afterwards,
you won't feel a thing.

214
00:13:23,623 --> 00:13:25,646
Besides, it's been
no earthly good to you, has it?

215
00:13:25,724 --> 00:13:27,486
-Like to look at the contract?
-Yes, please.

216
00:13:27,557 --> 00:13:29,160
There we are.

217
00:13:29,200 --> 00:13:33,149
Your soul's rather like your appendix:
totally expendable.

218
00:13:33,224 --> 00:13:35,560
There was a time
when it did have a function

219
00:13:35,600 --> 00:13:40,157
but nowadays the vast majority
of people never use it.

220
00:13:40,224 --> 00:13:42,655
Looks a bit complicated.

221
00:13:42,724 --> 00:13:44,656
It's a standard contract.

222
00:13:44,724 --> 00:13:47,656
Gives you seven wishes in accordance
with the mystic rules of life:

223
00:13:47,724 --> 00:13:52,157
seven days of the week, seven deadly sins,
seven seas, Seven Brides for Seven Brothers...

224
00:13:52,224 --> 00:13:53,560
Look, if you're not interested,

225
00:13:53,600 --> 00:13:57,213
I'm sure there's thousands of others
who'd jump at the opportunity.

226
00:13:58,358 --> 00:14:00,483
No, it's just a bit sudden,
that's all.

227
00:14:00,557 --> 00:14:03,100
Read it through
on your own time.

228
00:14:05,300 --> 00:14:07,460
"I, Stanley Moon,

229
00:14:07,500 --> 00:14:12,249
hereinafter and in the hereafter
to be known as 'the damned'"

230
00:14:12,324 --> 00:14:15,778
-The damned?
-It's a form of words. Legal jargon.

231
00:14:17,391 --> 00:14:20,788
"Do warrant that
I am the sole owner of my soul."

232
00:14:22,657 --> 00:14:26,385
But what about Margaret? Do you promise
that I'll have her all to myself?

233
00:14:26,458 --> 00:14:28,447
Sign that

234
00:14:29,458 --> 00:14:31,321
